        "excerpt": "Now King Ahasuerus laid a tribute on the land and on the coastlands of the sea.",
        "body": "The epilogue's opening verse has puzzled commentators. Why does the book end with a tax? Karen Jobes (NIVAC, *Esther*, 1999) and Jon Levenson (*Esther*, OTL, 1997) both note that the tribute notice functions as a frame-closing device, returning the reader to the world of imperial power that opened the book in chapter 1. Just as the book opened with a display of Ahasuerus's wealth and power (1:3-4), it closes with a display of his economic reach. Empire has not changed. The tribute levy (*mas*) extends over 'the land and the coastlands of the sea' — a merism meaning the whole empire. No territory escapes the imperial claim.\n\nThe word *mas* carries a specific semantic weight in the Hebrew Scriptures. It is used for Egypt's forced labor imposed on Israel (Exodus 1:11), for Solomon's corvée labor (1 Kings 5:13), and for the tribute Israel paid to stronger nations in defeat (Judges 1:28-35). It is the vocabulary of power exercised over subjects for the ruler's benefit. The narrator is not praising Ahasuerus; he is characterizing the system. This is the world in which Mordecai exercises his position — an empire that extracts.\n\nThe theological significance of the opening verse becomes clear only when read against verse 3. Empire imposes tribute; Mordecai seeks good and speaks shalom. The contrast is not between two individuals but between two ways of exercising power. The narrator sets the imperial logic in verse 1 in order to display an alternative logic in verse 3. The Jew at the second throne of Persia has not become the empire; he has remained himself within it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mas* (tribute, forced labor) shares vocabulary with Israel's Egyptian bondage (*Exodus 1:11*) and Solomon's building projects (*1 Kings 5:13*). *I ha-yam* (coastlands of the sea) is a biblical merism for geographic totality — cf. *Isaiah 42:10; 49:1*. *Erets* (land) as the inner domain paired with the coastlands as the outer boundary brackets the full extent of Persian sovereignty."
